However, in the heart of the district, one of the most unavoidable villages of the capital is hidden: the Batignolles. In fact, if we call the Batignolles a "village", it's not for nothing: once you walk around, you'll find the true spirit of neighborhood life.

The Batignolles district is full of immense green spaces. To take a poetic break, and why not meditate on the water's edge alongside the geese and ducks, there is nothing better than the Square des Batignolles. With its English style and its 16,000 m2, it offers a view worthy of an impressionist painting by Monet: a stream, trees, a waterfall and even a grotto serving as decorum. After that, sigh: it gets much better.

In some streets, Les Épinettes has also become a playground for contemporary architects. At 35 rue Lantiez, for example, the architects have dropped the white concrete for a facade of dark metal and glass, which combine to play on transparency. At 6-8 Villa des Épinettes, you can discover the "Film House", an astonishing house in the shape of a large camera, where light enters through the lens.

For an exemplary Sunday, start with a visit to rue de la Jonquière, to the independent bookshop L'usage du monde, which regularly organises meetings with authors of novels, essays and comics. Then stop a little further down the street at Irène et Bernard's, whose 13€ Sunday brunch is always packed. Finally, head for the Hasard Ludique, a former station on the Petite Ceinture that has been transformed into a cultural and festive venue. neighborhood_overview: There’s no other neighborhood that captures the charm of Paris quite like the historic district of Montmartre. Perched high atop the fumes and sounds of the city centre, with its tightly packed art deco houses and winding cobbled streets full of atmospheric cafes, all you need to enjoy this area is a pair of feet. Once home to the Parisian art and poetry community, the 18th arrondissement retains its intellectual beauty of days gone past; and with past residents including Picasso, Degas and Renoir, it’s no wonder there’s an air of bohemia about the place. \r\nWhether you brave the stairs of the Rue Foyatier or simply take the lift up the hill, the real mystique of Montmartre is found at the top.  At its pinnacle sits the Basilica of the Sacre Coeur, affording panoramic views of the city. Behind is a vibrant artist colony, with restaurants, shops and artists scribbling away at every corner.
